n shares the title of `ombudsman' with the PHSO, our</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.4pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.6pt">private sector remit in respect of financial services inevitably (and rightly) means that o</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.6pt">ur</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.6pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">focus and operation is somewhat different.</span></p><p style="margin:12.6pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.4pt">As you know, the Financial Ombudsman Service was established under the Financial</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.4pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.4pt">Services and Markets Act to resolve disputes between financial businesses and their</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.4pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.35pt">customers. It brought together a number of pr</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.35pt">edecessor ombudsman schemes under</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.35pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.7pt">one roof to create a `one stop shop' for financial services disputes. The service deals with</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.7pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.4pt">complaints involving banks, insurers, advisors and other businesses regulated by the</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.4pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.35pt">Financial Conduct Authority (FCA), as well a</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.35pt">s those made against consumer credit</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.35pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">businesses currently licensed by the Office of Fair Trading. In total we cover more than</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt"> 1</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">00,000 businesses ranging from the major banks to sole traders.</span></p><p style="margin:9pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.4pt">Our statutory remit is therefore somewhat different from the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.4pt">PHSO's. Unlike the PHSO, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.45pt">we have a statutory obligation to both look at and resolve all complaints referred to us </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">directly by consumers, except in quite limited circumstances — giving rise to significant volumes of complaints (around 500,000 currently rece</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">ived per year). Our role also has to be understood in the context of a wider regulatory regime for financial services — including </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.55pt">a statutory regulator of industry conduct — the Financial Conduct Authority — from whom we are operationally independent but w</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.55pt">ith whom we work closely. So while we share our </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.65pt">insight with both regulators and businesses, our focus is primarily on resolving individual </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.4pt">complaints, rather than necessarily looking at wider issues of commercial practice or </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.35pt">behaviour in the market. Anoth</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.35pt">er important difference is that, unlike the PHSO, if a </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.25pt">consumer accepts our decision then it is binding on the business concerned and </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">enforceable in court subject to an upper limit on binding awards of £150,000 a case.</span></p><p style="margin:9pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="585" height="15" alt="" style="float:left; margin:0pt" /><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.65pt">Those sorts of distinctions (the</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.65pt">re are of course many others) reflect the core</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.65pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.65pt">policy </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.55pt">purpose behind our organisation — namely as part of a wider set of</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.55pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.55pt">regulatory</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.55pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.6pt">architecture, to correct market failure in financial services by</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.6pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.6pt">removing the asymmetries of </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.4pt">power between businesses and </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.4pt">consumers</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.4pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.4pt">when engaged in disputes. So while there are </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.45pt">a number of analogies</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.45pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.45pt">between our services, we operate in a very different context from </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.6pt">the PHSO</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.6pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.6pt">— whose purpose is so closely tied to the wider delivery of public services and</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.6pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.6pt">Parliament's role in hol</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.6pt">ding the executive to account. Our evidence is therefore</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.6pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.6pt">inevitably </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">presented though that lens.</span></p><p style="margin:9pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.4pt">In terms of the complaints that come to us, in 2012/13 we handled 2,161,439 initial</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.4pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.35pt">enquiries in 55 languages. 508,881 enquiries were taken on as new cases (an </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.35pt">increase</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.35pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.4pt">of 92% on the year before) of which just under three quarters were about payment</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.4pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.6pt">protection insurance. Almost two thirds of last year's complaints (62%) related to the four</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.6pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">major high street banking groups.</span></p><p style="margin:12.6pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold">your questions</span></p><p style="font-size:10.5pt; line-height:200%; margin:12.6pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.7pt">Turning to the specific questions you raised in your letter: </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.3pt; text-decoration:underline">Harmonisation of Ombudsman schemes</span></p><p style="margin:10.8pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.7pt">1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.7pt">How do you share good practice with other ombudsmen, to improve processes and</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.7pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.3pt">customer service?</span></p><p style="margin:9pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">We engage with our fellow UK ombudsman schemes in a regular, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">structured way through</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.55pt">the well-established Ombudsman Association, of which Caroline Wayman (our Principal</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.55pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.65pt">Ombudsman and Legal Director) is an executive committee member. We also share best</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.65pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.55pt">practice with other financial ombudsman schemes across the world, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.55pt">through both informal</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.55pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.4pt">and formal networks. Ombudsman Association members regularly co-operate on issues</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.4pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">of shared interest, for example the recent work on managing the impact of Alternative</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.45pt">Business Structures (ABS) regulations.</span></p><p style="margin:9pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">We also enjoy warm and co-o</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">perative bilateral relationships at senior staff and board level with a number of ombudsman schemes — including financial ombudsman schemes across the world.</span></p><p style="margin:10.8pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.7pt">2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.7pt">What are your views on the creation of a single access point for complaints to all</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.7pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; font-style:italic">ombudsmen?</span></p><p style="margin:10.8pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">There is certainly opportunity to improve access to ombudsman services across the UK.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.3pt">And it is true that the fact that there are different schemes can cause consumers</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.3pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">confusion.</span></p><p style="margin:10.8pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.4pt">We regularly research consumer behaviour, as whatever access mechanism we hav</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.4pt">e </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">needs to meet consumer needs. The findings we have, however, show that consumers </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.6pt">don't search for `ombudsmen' — they look for specific resolution of their issue. So, if they </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">have an issue with their bank, they are likely to contact us, or a debt charity,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt"> whereas if </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.45pt">they have an issue with their NHS provider they are likely to contact advice agencies, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.65pt">patient groups or the PHSO. In our case regulatory rules require clear signposting of the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.45pt">ombudsman by financial businesses when they handle complaints.</span></p><p style="margin:10.8pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="586" height="14" alt="" style="float:left; margin:0pt" /><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.35pt">So, while a single access point for all complaints to all ombudsmen might appear an</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.35pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.6pt">attractive option, we would be concerned that it would simply add a new cost (of running a</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.6pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.55pt">new infrastructure) for a service which consumers would be unlikely to use, or se</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.55pt">e benefit</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.55pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.7pt">from. A single portal for ombudsman schemes may also (however inadvertently) limit the</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.7pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.6pt">consumer's understanding of non-ombudsman options available to them such as Citizen's</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.6pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.35pt">Advice, trading standards or in some cases alternative mediation schemes.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.35pt"> Of course,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.35pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">one could add those services to the portal too, but that risks becoming unwieldy.</span></p><p style="margin:10.8pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">The existing ombudsman schemes are good at cross-referring consumers to one another</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.4pt">on the occasions when that is necessary. With over two million customer contac</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.4pt">ts last</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.4pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.7pt">year, some of which end up being directed to other schemes, we have particularly strong</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.7pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.25pt">experience of this. It's also worth noting that the EU online portal for ombudsman</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.25pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.4pt">services — which is being implemented in parallel with the ADR directive — </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.4pt">will offer a</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.4pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.45pt">single entry point for consumers who have bought goods or services online.</span></p><p style="margin:12.6pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">We cannot see the benefit of another 'single' portal.</span></p><p style="margin:12.6pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.7pt">3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.7pt">What are your views on whether or not there should be a single public services</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.7pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.35pt">ombudsman in England, as there is i</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.35pt">n Scotland and Wales?</span></p><p style="margin:12.6pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">While we see the intellectual case for economies of scale and ease of access on the one</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.45pt">hand, and the benefits of specialisation on the other (see also question 6 below), in the</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.45pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.45pt">end this is a matter that is wholly outside our </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.45pt">jurisdiction and we have no particular view</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.45pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">on it.</span></p><p style="margin:12.6pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; text-decoration:underline">European Directive on Alternative Dispute Resolution</span></p><p style="margin:12.6pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.7pt">4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">What consideration have you given to the introduction of an EU Directive on ADR and </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.4pt">are you taking any action in response?</span></p><p style="margin:12.6pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">We are pleased to note that t</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">he Directive was based to a significant extent on UK best</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.75pt">practice, and believe that its implementation in the UK should build on the strong existing</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.75pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">arrangements for ADR of which our service is part.</span></p><p style="margin:12.6pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.65pt">The ADR Directive is of course significant for us. We </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.65pt">have been closely engaged with its</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.65pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">development, and we broadly welcome its provisions. We are looking at whether any</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.35pt">adjustments to our operations will be required as a result of the legislation which</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.35pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">transposes it into UK law.</span></p><p style="margin:12.6pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.7pt">5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.75pt">To </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.25pt">what extent do you believ</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.25pt">e the Directive will allow better and meaningful</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.25pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.45pt">comparisons in performance and sharing of practice across providers or agencies?</span></p><p style="margin:12.6pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">The Directive has two functions: the first is to harmonise basic standards and the second</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.4pt">is to improve access. Given the very</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.4pt"> varied types of ADR provision both within the UK</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.4pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.75pt">and the EU we think the publication of data mandated by Directive itself is unlikely to aid </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">meaningful comparisons between different providers.</span></p><p style="margin:9pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.55pt">It's also important to remember, as noted in the introduction </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.55pt">to our evidence, that variation</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.55pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">is not necessarily bad: different ombudsman schemes are — for good reasons — designed</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.3pt">in different ways, meaning that even where comparison may be possible it may not</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.3pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.45pt">always be meaningful or instructive, either for the consu</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.45pt">mer or other interested parties.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.45pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.55pt">We think the numbers can be useful — but they rarely tell the whole story.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.25pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="587" height="14" alt="" style="float:left; margin:0pt" /><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.25pt">That said, we do place a premium on transparency (we now publish ombudsman</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.25pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">decisions, and have always been very open about the basis on which </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">we make decisions,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">and about the trends in complaints by issue and by firm) and we welcome any</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">encouragement to transparency in ADR provision. If not telling in themselves, published</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">data can really help in bringing understanding to our work.</span></p><p style="margin:10.8pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.45pt">6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.45pt">To what exten</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.45pt">t do you think the Directive presents an opportunity to remodel the existing system of ADR to resolve possible existing overlaps, shortfalls and conflicts?</span></p><p style="margin:12.6pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">The ADR Directive is certainly an opportunity to look at the system we have and decide</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.7pt">whether it's </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.7pt">the sort of system that parliament wants for the UK. And there is no doubt that</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.7pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.45pt">overlaps and shortfalls exist. For example, if you're buying a house then your lawyer will</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.45pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.45pt">be covered by one ombudsman, your mortgage provider another, and your estate agent</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.45pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.3pt">by</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.3pt"> yet another. There are gaps too — no ombudsman, for example, covers advice to</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.3pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.4pt">switch occupational pension schemes.</span></p><p style="margin:12.6pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">We do have a good record of addressing these gaps and overlaps, in collaboration with</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">other ombudsman schemes where necessary. Overall, the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">UK's ADR system functions</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">fairly well and the Directive won't necessarily force reform either.</span></p><p style="margin:10.8pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.45pt">That said, the Directive and the domestic legislation it spawns do represent a good</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.45pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">opportunity for the government to take stock of the ADR landscape, and to ask</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt"> some</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.45pt">questions about what approach we think is best for consumers and industry. There is a</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.45pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.7pt">case for the current landscape, characterised by a large number of discrete and specialist</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.7pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.6pt">ombudsman services to whom regulators and the industry can relate and dev</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.6pt">elop close</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.6pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.45pt">relationships, and most of whom operate in a way that looks a little like the courts. We</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.45pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.45pt">can see the appeal of this network of smaller, specialised schemes.</span></p><p style="margin:12.6pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.3pt">But we can also see the logic of a landscape in which networks of fewer and larger</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.3pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.55pt">schemes operate. As well as being easier to navigate for consumers, they benefit from</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.55pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.35pt">economies of scale that give them increased versatility and resilience to peaks (and</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.35pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.65pt">troughs) in demand — including those caused by mass complaints like PPI and changes i</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.65pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.65pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">market or consumer behaviour, which can be hard to forecast. Bigger schemes can also </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.65pt">apply their learning and expertise across sectors and invest in outreach and insight, while </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">adjusting more easily to changes in scope and jurisdiction.</span></p><p style="margin:12.6pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.55pt">Our own experienc</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.55pt">e suggests that some of the best of both worlds may be possible. With </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.75pt">work spanning two regulators, we have experience of managing work from more than one </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.55pt">jurisdiction, tailoring rules and approaches where necessary depending on the relevant </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.25pt">regulatory env</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.25pt">ironment, and more generally handling the technical and cultural </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.45pt">differences between sectors described elsewhere in this evidence. Other ombudsman </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">schemes have similar experience.</span></p><p style="margin:12.6pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">Finally, in terms of the Directive, it's important to note that its provisio</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">ns on access are geared towards the relationships between consumers and traders. We don't have the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.65pt">experience to comment on far its approach might usefully translate to the slightly different </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">context of public sector ombudsmanry.</span></p><p style="margin:9pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.45pt">7.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.7pt">How can those involved in </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.7pt">dispute resolution, but who aren't covered by the Directive, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.45pt">ensure that they are meeting the same expected standards of quality as those who </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.4pt">are covered by it?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.65pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="587" height="14" alt="" style="float:left; margin:0pt" /><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.65pt">As stressed in my answer to question 5, it's important to note that different ombudsman </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">schemes do different things. Some resolve business-to-business disputes, while others </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.25pt">handle consumer-to-business ones. Some deal with very complex cases requiring </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.6pt">specialist knowledge and detailed research, while others handle relatively straightforward </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.4pt">m</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.4pt">atters (and of course some — like us — do both). Some are obliged to handle all </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.6pt">complaints that come to them, while others are not. Some (like PHSO and us) have an </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.65pt">obligation to share their insights with regulators and others, while others don't. And every</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.65pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.25pt">scheme has different stakeholders with often very different requirements and </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">expectations.</span></p><p style="margin:9pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">Therefore, while high standards across the board are important for all of us, it isn't clear </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.7pt">that one could or should impose precise definitions of what constitutes</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.7pt"> high standards for </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.55pt">application across the full range of schemes. Instead, it makes sense for the Directive to </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.3pt">impose basic standards at a high level — which is exactly what it does. Then, more </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.55pt">detailed standards should be determined by the relevant author</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.55pt">ity on a sector-by-sector </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.3pt">basis, through the specification (and, where applicable, tendering) of individual </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">ombudsman schemes. This specific standard-setting will be the real driver of standards, and will apply just as much to schemes outside the scope of </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">the Directive as within it.</span></p><p style="margin:12.6pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">It's also important that flexibility should be shown within individual schemes as well as </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.4pt">between </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.4pt">them: a simple case can and should be dealt with quickly, whoever is dealing </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.55pt">with it, while more complex cases should get the time</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.55pt"> and attention they need. Ultimately this is in the consumer's interest: inflexible standards will always have to be set at a level </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">that's reasonable for the slowest, most complex cases, which would be unacceptably </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.45pt">frustrating for consumers and businesses </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.45pt">involved with simple complaints.</span></p><p style="margin:12.6pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.8pt">8. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.3pt">How can the government ensure against the proliferation of excessive numbers of</span><br /><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.4pt">different dispute resolution bodies and mechanisms (and should it be doing so)?</span></p><p style="margin:12.6pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.45pt">In my answer to question 6, I said we believe the overall approach taken by Government </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.6pt">to shaping the ADR landscape should depend on what factors it wishes to prioritise in the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">provision of ADR services for consumers. Relative proliferation might be desira</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">ble if we </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.6pt">thought consumers would benefit most from specialised services, with strong but narrow </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.75pt">industry and regulator relationships. Alternatively, consolidation may be best if we thought </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.3pt">consumers would benefit most from a marketplace that shared learni</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.3pt">ng, was more </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.45pt">resilient to mass complaints and could achieve economies of scale.</span></p><p style="margin:9pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">In any case, if Government does take the opportunity to re-shape the ADR landscape it must be careful to preserve the one overriding principle of all ombudsmen — i.e. their ind</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">ependence. As with any quasi-judicial body, an ombudsman relies on there being </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.45pt">confidence (among both consumers and traders) that the scheme is genuinely impartial. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">So in contemplating any future changes to the ADR set up, it's essential that services are </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">not subject to any funding structures that incentivise partisanship, or the perception of it. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.4pt">An ombudsman must not give the impression of having been captured by a financial </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.55pt">interest to find in favour of one group or the other.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="587" height="14" alt="" style="float:left; margin:0pt" /><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">Therefore, while a polluter-pays model which provides good value for money remains the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.55pt">most desirable approach, the use of competition as a means of achieving value for money </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.3pt">needs to be considered carefully. For example, any competitive process whereby </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.4pt">om</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.4pt">budsmen compete to handle an individual business's complaints is likely to lead to a </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.55pt">race to the bottom as far as consumers are concerned. Even if there is no change in the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.2pt">substance of decisions, it's clear that a service's processes and approaches will b</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.2pt">e </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.7pt">geared to suit its customer (the business) rather than the consumer, which risks deterring </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">consumers from complaining. It would also introduce incentives against an ombudsman making tough decisions which are unpopular with the industry concerned.</span></p><p style="margin:9pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.55pt">I hope </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.55pt">these answers are useful for your inquiry. </span></p><p style="margin:9pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.7pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:9pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.7pt">November 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>